article.description: Tennessee, the only team to appear in every Sweet 16, did it again with a victory over Virginia.
article.headline: Lady Vols roll to 42-0 at home in NCAA Tournament
article.linkText: It wouldn't be a Sweet 16 without Tennessee
article.story:
KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Kara Lawson found a small flaw in
Tennessee's home-court advantage during the NCAA tournament.

	   "You still have to go to class when the other teams don't have
to go to class,'' Lawson said.

	   So far, that hasn't been a distraction.

	   Shyra Ely had 17 points and nine rebounds and Gwen Jackson added
13 points as Tennessee advanced to its 22nd straight round of 16
with an 81-51 win over Virginia in the Mideast Regional on Monday
night.

	   The top-seeded Lady Vols (30-4), the only team to appear in
every regional semifinal since the NCAA women's tournament began in
1982, led from the tipoff and were hardly challenged in improving
their NCAA home record to 42-0.

	   Tennessee, also hosting the regional, will play the winner of
Tuesday night's game between South Carolina and Penn State on
Saturday.

	   That means four days of classes until then and just two more
home games to reach the Final Four.

	   "Normally, if we were (traveling) in the tournament we'd be
sleeping in or going over the game plan, video or scouting,''
Lawson said.

	   Apparently, Tennessee still had plenty of time for that.

	   The No. 8 seed Cavaliers (17-14) struggled the entire game to
contain Tennessee's offense.

	   The Lady Vols led 33-24 at halftime and increased the lead to 17
before Virginia pulled within 12 with 10:45 remaining. Tennessee,
having no desire to make the game close, went on an 18-4 run to
increase its lead to 26.

	   Brittany Jackson and Shanna Zolman each hit 3s to start the
spurt as the partisan crowd roared. Zolman hit another 3-pointer
and the Lady Vols led 68-42 with 6:15 to go, quelling any chance of
a late Virginia rally.

	   "It's great to see our basketball team open game No. 2 with
great intensity on the defensive end and obviously, a commitment to
transition,'' Tennessee coach Pat Summitt said. "I thought we got
a lot of good looks in the first half, looking a little overanxious
at times. We settled down at halftime.''

	   Loree Moore finished with 13 points, Lawson had 11 and Zolman
10.

	   Cherrise Graham scored 14 points for the Cavaliers, who shot 27
percent (17-of-61) from the floor.

	   "We played very hard and had the game plan. We just could not
put the ball in the basket,'' Virginia coach Debbie Ryan said.
"When we got to the 10-minute mark of the second half, that is
when the floodgates opened. We couldn't stop them.''

	   Virginia has been Tennessee's most frequent opponent in the
tournament. The Lady Vols are 8-1 against the Cavaliers, with the
lone loss coming in 1990 when Virginia won the regional final in
Norfolk, Va., and prevented Tennessee from playing in the Final
Four it was hosting.

	   The Lady Vols have won six in a row since then, including the
1991 national championship over Virginia.

	   The Cavaliers lost in the second round for only the second time
in 14 games.

	   Tennessee extended its halftime lead to 16 with a 7-0 run in the
first 1:20 of the second half. Lawson hit a 3 off an inbounds pass,
Gwen Jackson scored inside and Ely made a layup after Virginia
turned the ball over at the other end.

	   The Cavaliers wouldn't go away, trimming the lead to 11 a minute
later after LaTonya Blue made a 3.

	   Scoring in transition after another Virginia turnover and then a
Tennessee steal, the Lady Vols went up by 15.

	   Virginia cut it to 12 after a 3-pointer by Liz Sahin, and
Tennessee missed three shots.

	   Summitt, wanting to see the half-court offense work, yelled
"45'' from the sideline. Ely passed under the basket to Gwen
Jackson, who scored the easy layup and gave Tennessee a 50-36 lead
with 10:55 remaining.

	   Ely scored 11 of her points in the first eight minutes of the
game as Tennessee went ahead 14-3.
